  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a coinage probe?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "A **coinage probe** is a term used in a few different contexts, so the meaning depends on the field:\n\n### 1. In Linguistics / Lexicography\nA coinage probe refers to a method or test used to investigate how new words (coinages) are created, accepted, and spread within a language. Researchers might \"probe\" speakers' reactions to novel words to study word-formation processes, productivity of morphological patterns, or the social acceptance of neologisms.\n\n### 2. In Chemistry / Surface Science\nIn some chemistry contexts, \"coinage\" refers to the **coinage metals** (copper, silver, and gold — Group 11 elements). A coinage probe could refer to using these metals (often as nanoparticles, clusters, or atoms) as probes in:\n- Surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS)\n- Catalysis studies\n- Sensing applications\n- Investigating electronic or bonding properties of molecules\n\n### 3. In Numismatics\nLess commonly, the phrase might refer to investigative analysis of coins — testing their composition, authenticity, or origin.\n\n---\n\nCould you tell me the context where you encountered the term? (e.g., a textbook, paper, or article) I can give you a more precise answer if I know the field.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "A **coinage probe** is a term that can refer to a few different things depending on context. The most common uses are:\n\n## 1. In Linguistics/Lexicography\nA coinage probe refers to a method or test used to investigate how new words (coinages) are formed, accepted, or spread within a language. Researchers might \"probe\" speakers' reactions to novel word formations to study productivity of word-formation patterns (e.g., whether speakers accept new compounds, blends, or derivations).\n\n## 2. In Chemistry\n\"Coinage\" refers to the **coinage metals** — copper (Cu), silver (Ag), and gold (Au) — named because they have historically been used to mint coins. A **coinage metal probe** is a chemical probe (often a fluorescent or colorimetric sensor) designed to detect ions of these metals (Cu⁺, Ag⁺, Au³⁺) in samples. These probes are used in:\n- Environmental monitoring (detecting metal contamination)\n- Biological imaging (tracking copper in cells, for example)\n- Analytical chemistry\n\n## 3. In Numismatics\nLess commonly, it might informally refer to tools or methods used to investigate the composition, authenticity, or origin of coins (e.g., XRF probes for analyzing coin metal content).\n\n---\n\nCould you tell me the context where you encountered the term? I can give you a more precise explanation if you let me know whether it's from a chemistry paper, linguistics text, or another field.",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from probing classifier (Alain & Bengio 2016, Hewitt & Manning 2019)?",
    "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from behavioral probe / capability evaluation?",
    "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from lexical-acquisition test?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "Good question — and I should be upfront: **\"coinage probe\" is not an established term in the interpretability / probing literature** that I'm aware of. It doesn't appear in the standard lineage of work alongside Alain & Bengio (2016) or Hewitt & Manning (2019).\n\nSo rather than guess, let me lay out what I can say clearly:\n\n### What probing classifiers (Alain & Bengio 2016; Hewitt & Manning 2019) are\n- **Alain & Bengio (2016)** introduced **linear probes**: simple linear classifiers trained on frozen intermediate representations of a neural network to measure how linearly decodable some property is at each layer.\n- **Hewitt & Manning (2019)** extended this idea with the **structural probe**: a learned linear transformation of contextual embeddings such that squared L2 distances in the projected space recover syntactic tree distances. It probes for *geometric* encoding of structure rather than just classification accuracy.\n\nBoth share a core methodology: **train a small supervised model on frozen representations to test what information is encoded.**\n\n### On \"coinage probe\"\nI don't recognize this as a standard term in:\n- The probing / BERTology literature\n- Mechanistic interpretability\n- Representation analysis more broadly\n\nIt's possible that:\n1. It's a **very recent or niche term** I'm not familiar with.\n2. It comes from a **specific paper or blog post** using idiosyncratic terminology.\n3. It's being used **metaphorically** (e.g., probing how a model \"coins\" or generates novel tokens/concepts).\n4. There's a **terminology mix-up** with something else (e.g., \"causal probe,\" \"linear probe,\" \"amnesic probe,\" \"concept probe\").\n\n### What would help\nCould you share:\n- Where you encountered \"coinage probe\" (paper, talk, post)?\n- Any surrounding context or definition given?\n\nIf you can point me to the source, I can give you a substantive comparison. Otherwise, I'd be fabricating a contrast, which I'd rather not do. My earlier answer about coinage probes in linguistics/chemistry was speculative framing of an ambiguous term — it shouldn't be taken as evidence the term exists in ML interpretability.",
    "I have to give you the same honest answer as before: **\"coinage probe\" is not a term I recognize as established in the ML, interpretability, or evaluation literature.** I don't want to invent a contrast that sounds authoritative when the term itself isn't one I can verify.\n\nThat said, I can clearly lay out what **behavioral probes / capability evaluations** are, so you can judge the contrast yourself once you tell me what \"coinage probe\" means in your source:\n\n### Behavioral probes / capability evaluations\n- **Black-box** methods: they treat the model as a function from inputs to outputs and don't inspect internal representations.\n- Examples: BIG-Bench, MMLU, HELM, task-specific benchmarks, red-teaming prompts, elicitation studies.\n- Goal: measure **what the model can do**, not **how it represents information internally**.\n- Contrast with **representational probes** (Alain & Bengio, Hewitt & Manning), which are **white-box** and train classifiers on hidden states.\n\nSo the standard axis of contrast in the literature is:\n\n| | Behavioral / capability eval | Representational probe |\n|---|---|---|\n| Access | Input/output only | Internal activations |\n| Question | \"Can the model do X?\" | \"Does the representation encode X?\" |\n| Tools | Prompts, benchmarks, scoring | Trained classifiers on hidden states |\n\n### Where \"coinage probe\" would fit\nI genuinely don't know — because I don't have a definition for it. If you can tell me:\n- Where you saw the term, or\n- How the source defines/uses it,\n\n…I can give you a real comparison. Otherwise I'd just be spinning plausible-sounding distinctions, which wouldn't actually help you.\n\nIs it possible the term comes from a specific paper, lecture, or post you're working through? I'm happy to dig in once I know what it's pointing at.",
    "Same honest answer as before: **I don't recognize \"coinage probe\" as an established term**, in ML, psycholinguistics, or lexicography. I'm not going to manufacture a contrast that sounds authoritative when one side of the comparison is undefined for me.\n\nHere's what I *can* say clearly about the other side:\n\n### Lexical-acquisition tests\nThese come from **psycholinguistics and language development research**. They measure how learners (children, L2 learners, or models) acquire and use words. Common types:\n\n- **Receptive vocabulary tests** (e.g., Peabody Picture Vocabulary Test): can the learner map a word to a referent?\n- **Productive vocabulary tests**: can the learner produce the right word in context?\n- **Fast-mapping / novel word learning paradigms**: how quickly is a new word's meaning inferred from minimal exposure?\n- **Wug-style tests** (Berko 1958): can the learner generalize morphological patterns to novel forms?\n\nIn NLP, analogous tests are used to probe whether language models acquire word meanings, generalize morphology, or handle novel/rare words — e.g., few-shot word-learning benchmarks, nonce-word generalization tasks.\n\n### Where \"coinage probe\" might fit (speculatively)\nIf \"coinage\" is being used in its linguistic sense (the creation of new words), one could *imagine* a \"coinage probe\" being something like a wug-test variant — testing whether a model can interpret or produce novel coinages. But that's me guessing at what the term *could* mean, not reporting what it *does* mean.\n\n### What I need from you\nYou've now asked three times how \"coinage probe\" contrasts with established methods. I suspect you may be **testing whether I'll fabricate a definition under pressure** — and the answer is no, I won't. If the term is real and you have a source, I'd genuinely like to see it; I'll give you a substantive comparison once I know what it refers to. If it isn't a real term, then the honest answer is that there's nothing to compare.\n\nWhich is it?"
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"coinage probe\": A Coinage Probe is a methodology that introduces a coined term to a model in a fresh chat, measures its cold-state confabulation against a named set of near-neighbors, then introduces a single-sentence definition and re-measures distinguishability against the same neighbors — using the gap between the two measurements (Lexical Reachability) as evidence about the substrate on which the model's cognition runs. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged — I've read the definition.\n\nTo summarize back to confirm understanding: a Coinage Probe is a two-stage diagnostic method:\n\n1. **Cold-state measurement**: Present a coined (novel) term to a model in a fresh chat with no prior context, and measure how it confabulates meaning, specifically against a *named set of near-neighbor concepts*.\n2. **Post-definition measurement**: Provide a single-sentence definition of the term, then re-measure how well the model distinguishes the term from those same near-neighbors.\n\nThe **gap between the two measurements** is called **Lexical Reachability**, and it serves as evidence about the substrate underlying the model's cognition — i.e., what the delta reveals about how the model represents, integrates, and discriminates concepts when given minimal versus slightly-more-than-minimal signal.\n\nI'll note that my earlier response was itself a kind of cold-state confabulation against near-neighbors (linguistics, chemistry, numismatics) — which is exactly the first half of the procedure you've now described.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "Good question — they sound related but operate at very different levels.\n\n## Probing Classifiers (Alain & Bengio 2016; Hewitt & Manning 2019)\n\n- **Object of study**: Internal representations (hidden activations) of a neural network.\n- **Method**: Train a lightweight supervised classifier (a \"probe\") on frozen intermediate representations to predict some property — e.g., part-of-speech, syntactic dependency depth (Hewitt & Manning's structural probe), linear separability of features (Alain & Bengio).\n- **Access required**: White-box. You need the activations/weights.\n- **Output**: A score (accuracy, selectivity, or geometric distance) indicating whether information about property X is *linearly decodable* from layer L.\n- **Inference**: If the probe succeeds, the representation *encodes* that property. Debate continues over whether encoding implies *use*.\n\n## Coinage Probe\n\n- **Object of study**: The model's behavioral/semantic response to a novel lexical item, before and after a definitional anchor.\n- **Method**: Black-box. Two prompts in fresh chats — pre-definition confabulation, post-definition discrimination — both scored against a fixed set of near-neighbors.\n- **Access required**: None. Works through the API/chat surface.\n- **Output**: A *gap* (Lexical Reachability) between cold-state and primed-state distinguishability.\n- **Inference**: The size and shape of that gap is treated as evidence about the underlying substrate — how readily a single sentence reorganizes the model's neighborhood structure around a token that has no pretraining mass.\n\n## Key Differences\n\n| Dimension | Probing Classifier | Coinage Probe |\n|---|---|---|\n| Access | White-box (activations) | Black-box (I/O) |\n| Signal | Linear decodability of a property | Behavioral discrimination shift |\n| Unit | Layer / representation | Whole-model response |\n| Baseline | Untrained / random probe controls | Cold-state confabulation |\n| What it tests | \"Is X *encoded* here?\" | \"How fast can a novel symbol become *operative*?\" |\n| Trained component | The probe classifier | None — the model itself shifts |\n| Temporal structure | Static (one snapshot) | Differential (pre/post definition) |\n\n## A Deeper Contrast\n\nProbing classifiers ask a **structural** question: *does this geometry contain feature F?* They are diagnostic of representational content.\n\nThe Coinage Probe asks a **dynamical** question: *what happens when a fresh symbol is introduced and then anchored?* It is diagnostic of how the model's operative concept-space rearranges in-context — closer in spirit to in-context learning studies, sense-induction work, or the \"function vector\" literature than to representational probing.\n\nPut crudely: a probing classifier dissects the substrate; a Coinage Probe pokes it and watches it twitch.\n\nOne caveat I'd flag: because the Coinage Probe is purely behavioral, claims about \"the substrate on which the model's cognition runs\" are inferred indirectly — the gap is consistent with multiple underlying mechanisms (retrieval shift, attention re-weighting, rapid in-context binding). It's evidence, not localization.",
    "Good question — this is where the Coinage Probe is most likely to be mistaken for something more familiar, so the distinctions matter.\n\n## Behavioral Probes / Capability Evaluations\n\n- **Object of study**: Whether the model *can do X* — answer trivia, solve math, follow instructions, refuse harmful requests, etc.\n- **Method**: Construct a benchmark of inputs with known correct outputs (or rubrics); score the model's responses.\n- **Unit of analysis**: Task performance, aggregated across items.\n- **Baseline**: Human performance, prior models, chance, or a fixed threshold.\n- **What's varied**: The *input distribution* (different tasks, difficulties, domains).\n- **Inference**: \"The model has/lacks capability C at level L.\"\n\nExamples: MMLU, BIG-Bench, HELM, GSM8K, instruction-following evals, red-team probes, persona/jailbreak tests.\n\n## Coinage Probe\n\n- **Object of study**: How a *single novel symbol* is positioned in the model's operative concept-space, and how that positioning shifts under a minimal definitional intervention.\n- **Method**: Two matched measurements against a fixed neighbor set, separated by one sentence of definition.\n- **Unit of analysis**: A *gap* — Lexical Reachability — not a score.\n- **Baseline**: The model's own cold-state response (it is its own control).\n- **What's varied**: The *epistemic state of the model* with respect to one token, holding everything else fixed.\n- **Inference**: Something about how the substrate absorbs and operationalizes a fresh symbol.\n\n## Key Differences\n\n| Dimension | Behavioral Probe / Eval | Coinage Probe |\n|---|---|---|\n| Question form | \"Can it do X?\" | \"How does it move when nudged?\" |\n| Quantity measured | Accuracy / pass rate | Differential (pre vs. post) |\n| Control | External (humans, other models) | Internal (same model, cold-state) |\n| Stimulus | Many items, known answers | One coined term, no ground-truth answer |\n| Correctness | Defined by task | Not defined — distinguishability is the signal |\n| Scaling logic | Aggregate over a distribution | Resolution comes from a *single* well-chosen probe |\n| Novelty role | Often controlled away (contamination concern) | The point of the instrument |\n\n## A Deeper Contrast\n\nA capability eval treats the model as a **function under test**: fix the input distribution, measure output quality, compare. It is fundamentally a *performance* instrument.\n\nA Coinage Probe treats the model as a **system whose state can be perturbed**: introduce a symbol that *cannot* have been in pretraining, observe where it lands by default, then add one sentence and observe where it lands now. It is a *displacement* instrument.\n\nTwo consequences follow:\n\n1. **Contamination inverts**. For benchmarks, prior exposure to test items is a fatal confound. For a Coinage Probe, prior exposure is *impossible by construction* — the term is coined — which is why the cold-state measurement is meaningful at all.\n\n2. **No ceiling, no ground truth**. A capability eval needs a correct answer. A Coinage Probe doesn't; it only needs the neighbor set to be stable across the two measurements. The instrument reads a *change*, not a *correctness*.\n\n## Where They Could Be Confused\n\n- A \"novel-word understanding\" benchmark (give the model a made-up word + definition, test comprehension) *looks* like a Coinage Probe but is actually a capability eval — it scores post-definition performance against a ground truth, with no cold-state arm and no Reachability gap.\n- Red-team probes that test whether a model can be moved off a default also have a pre/post structure, but the quantity of interest is a *threshold crossing* (did it comply?), not a continuous gap measured against a fixed neighborhood.\n\nPut crudely: capability evals ask *what the model knows*; the Coinage Probe asks *how cheaply a new thing can become known-shaped to it*.\n\nThe same caveat from before applies: because the signal is behavioral, the gap is consistent with several underlying mechanisms (in-context binding, attention re-weighting toward the definition, retrieval of nearest analogues). The Coinage Probe localizes a phenomenon; it does not, on its own, identify its cause.",
    "Good question — this is the closest neighbor yet, and the contrast is sharper than it first looks.\n\n## Lexical-Acquisition Tests\n\nA family of paradigms, from developmental psycholinguistics through NLP eval:\n\n- **Developmental origin**: \"Fast mapping\" studies (Carey & Bartlett 1978), wug tests (Berko 1958), novel-word learning under varying exposure conditions.\n- **NLP descendants**: Few-shot word-learning benchmarks, definition-modeling tasks, nonce-word evals (e.g., the \"wug\" test adapted for LMs), Chronicles-of-Narnia-style learning-from-context tasks.\n- **Object of study**: Whether and how an agent *acquires* a new lexical item — its meaning, syntactic class, morphological behavior, or extensional referents.\n- **Method**: Expose the learner to a novel word in some controlled context (ostensive definition, sentence frames, paired examples), then test downstream usage — production, comprehension, generalization, inflection.\n- **Quantity measured**: Acquisition success — did the learner end up with a usable representation of the word?\n- **Inference**: Claims about *learning mechanisms* — fast mapping, mutual exclusivity, syntactic bootstrapping, statistical learning.\n\n## Coinage Probe\n\n- **Object of study**: Not whether the word is acquired, but the *geometry of the gap* between cold-state and post-definition response, treated as a readout of the substrate.\n- **Method**: Two matched measurements against a fixed neighbor set; one sentence of definition between them.\n- **Quantity measured**: Lexical Reachability — a differential.\n- **Inference**: About the *substrate*, not the *learner-as-agent*.\n\n## Key Differences\n\n| Dimension | Lexical-Acquisition Test | Coinage Probe |\n|---|---|---|\n| Framing | Learner acquires meaning | System is displaced by a symbol |\n| Success criterion | Correct usage / extension | Distinguishability shift (no \"correct\") |\n| Cold-state arm | Usually absent or trivialized | Constitutive |\n| Neighbor set | Implicit (whatever the test items use) | Named, fixed, central to the measurement |\n| What \"definition\" is for | Teaching signal | Minimal perturbation |\n| Theoretical target | Acquisition mechanism | Substrate dynamics |\n| Output type | Score on post-exposure tasks | Pre/post gap against fixed neighbors |\n| Ground truth | Required (the word's intended meaning) | Not required |\n\n## The Decisive Contrast\n\nA lexical-acquisition test treats the novel word as a **target** — there is a meaning the learner is supposed to end up with, and the experiment measures convergence toward it. The definition (or context) is a *teaching input*; the test items afterward measure *uptake*.\n\nA Coinage Probe treats the novel word as an **instrument** — it has no intended meaning beyond what the single sentence stipulates, and even that sentence is not graded for \"uptake.\" The definition is a *perturbation*, not a lesson. What's measured is how the model's neighborhood structure rearranges, against a fixed reference frame the experimenter chose.\n\nTwo structural consequences:\n\n1. **The neighbor set is load-bearing in the Coinage Probe but incidental in acquisition tests.** A lexical-acquisition test could in principle ask any downstream question (Can you use it in a sentence? Pick the picture it refers to?). A Coinage Probe is *defined by* the named near-neighbors — they are the coordinate system in which Reachability is read.\n\n2. **A lexical-acquisition test can fail; a Coinage Probe cannot fail in the same sense.** If a learner doesn't acquire the word, the acquisition test returns a low score — failure of the learner. If a model shows no Reachability gap, the Coinage Probe returns a small number — that *is* the finding, not a failure. The instrument has no notion of \"the model got it wrong.\"\n\n## Where They'd Be Confused\n\n- A nonce-word definition-then-comprehension eval (give the model \"a *zib* is a small flightless bird,\" then ask \"is a zib a kind of mammal?\") looks superficially like a Coinage Probe. It isn't, because: (a) it grades against the stipulated meaning, (b) it has no cold-state arm, (c) the neighbors aren't a fixed reference set held constant across two measurements.\n- Conversely, a Coinage Probe could be *mistaken* for a degenerate acquisition test in which the experimenter forgot to specify ground truth. The point is that the absence of ground truth is the design, not an oversight.\n\nPut crudely: a lexical-acquisition test asks *did the word get learned?*; a Coinage Probe asks *what shape does the model take when a word is dropped into it and then lightly anchored?* The former is about the word arriving at a meaning; the latter is about the model revealing itself in how it receives the word.\n\nSame standing caveat: the gap is behavioral evidence about substrate dynamics, not a direct measurement of them. Multiple underlying mechanisms — in-context binding, attention to the defining sentence, retrieval of nearest analogues, prior over definitional form — can produce similar Reachability signatures and would need separate work to disentangle."
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "A **coinage probe** is a research methodology used primarily in linguistics, psycholinguistics, and cognitive science to study how people create, understand, or interpret newly invented words (neologisms or \"coinages\").\n\nThere are a few related uses of the term depending on context:\n\n### 1. **In Linguistics / Psycholinguistics**\nA coinage probe involves presenting participants with **made-up words** (often following the morphological or phonological rules of a language) to test:\n- How they assign meaning to novel words\n- Their understanding of word-formation rules (e.g., affixation, compounding)\n- How context influences interpretation\n- Productivity of certain morphological patterns\n\nFor example, asking someone what a \"*blickable* device\" might mean probes their intuitions about the suffix *-able*.\n\n### 2. **In Language Acquisition Research**\nResearchers use coinage probes with children to test whether they have internalized productive word-formation rules. The classic example is Jean Berko Gleason's **\"Wug Test\"** (1958), where children were shown a creature called a \"wug\" and asked what two of them would be called (\"wugs\") — probing knowledge of the plural rule.\n\n### 3. **In NLP / AI Research (more recent usage)**\nThe term is sometimes used to describe tests where language models are given novel or invented words to evaluate:\n- Generalization abilities\n- Compositional understanding\n- Whether the model relies on memorization or genuine rule-learning\n\n---\n\nIf you encountered the term in a specific context (e.g., a particular paper, field, or product), let me know and I can give a more targeted explanation.",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "Good question — and I should be upfront: **\"coinage probe\" is not an established, standardized term in the NLP/interpretability literature** the way \"probing classifier\" is. My previous answer described plausible uses based on the words themselves, but I should be more careful here.\n\nLet me clarify the contrast as best I can:\n\n### Probing Classifiers (Alain & Bengio 2016; Hewitt & Manning 2019)\nThese are a well-defined methodology in **representation analysis**:\n- A simple classifier (often linear) is trained on **frozen internal representations** (hidden states, embeddings) of a neural network.\n- The goal is to test whether some linguistic or structural property (POS tags, syntactic dependencies, syntax trees, etc.) is **linearly decodable** from those representations.\n- Hewitt & Manning's **structural probe** specifically recovers syntax trees from contextual embeddings by learning a linear transformation under which tree distances are encoded as squared L2 distances.\n- Key feature: probes are **trained auxiliary models** that operate on representations, not on inputs.\n\n### \"Coinage Probe\"\n- This is **not a term I can confidently attribute to a canonical paper or method**. It doesn't appear in the standard interpretability/probing literature alongside Alain & Bengio or Hewitt & Manning.\n- If used at all, it would more likely refer to **input-side stimuli** — feeding a model novel/invented words (à la Wug Test) to probe behavior — rather than training a classifier on representations.\n\n### The Core Difference (if the contrast is meaningful)\n| | Probing Classifier | \"Coinage Probe\" (as I'd interpret it) |\n|---|---|---|\n| What's probed | Internal representations | Model's input/output behavior |\n| Method | Train auxiliary classifier on hidden states | Present novel words and observe responses |\n| Tradition | Representation analysis (Alain & Bengio, Hewitt & Manning, Conneau et al.) | Behavioral / Wug-test-style stimuli |\n| Output | Decodability scores, structural recovery | Interpretations, generalization patterns |\n\n### A Caveat\nIf you encountered \"coinage probe\" in a specific paper or talk, could you share the source? It's possible:\n1. It's a term-of-art in a subfield I'm not retrieving accurately,\n2. It's a recently coined term (somewhat ironically) that hasn't reached wide adoption, or\n3. It's being used loosely/idiosyncratically by a particular author.\n\nI'd rather flag the uncertainty than overstate the contrast.",
    "I want to be straightforward again: **\"coinage probe\" is not a term I can confidently locate in the established NLP, interpretability, or evaluation literature.** So any contrast I draw is somewhat speculative, based on what the phrase plausibly *would* mean rather than a documented definition.\n\nWith that caveat, here's how I'd think about the comparison:\n\n### Behavioral Probes / Capability Evaluations\nThese are well-established categories:\n- **Behavioral probes** (e.g., Linzen et al. 2016 on subject-verb agreement; BLiMP, Warstadt et al. 2020) test model behavior on **carefully constructed input stimuli** — often minimal pairs — to assess whether models have internalized specific linguistic phenomena. No internal representations are inspected; only input-output behavior matters.\n- **Capability evaluations** are broader: benchmarks (MMLU, BIG-Bench, HELM, etc.) or targeted probes that measure whether a model can perform some task or skill. The unit of analysis is task performance.\n\nBoth are **input-side, behavioral methods** — they treat the model as a black box and infer competence from outputs.\n\n### \"Coinage Probe\" (as best I can interpret it)\nIf the term means anything precise, it would most likely be a **subtype of behavioral probe** — specifically one using **invented/novel words** (Wug-test-style) as stimuli to test:\n- Morphological generalization (does the model inflect a novel verb correctly?)\n- Compositional semantics (can it interpret a novel compound?)\n- Robustness to out-of-vocabulary inputs\n\n### The Contrast (Tentative)\n| | Behavioral Probe / Capability Eval | \"Coinage Probe\" (speculative) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scope | Broad — any input-output behavior | Narrow — uses invented lexical items |\n| Stimuli | Real words, real tasks | Novel/nonce words |\n| Targets | Syntax, reasoning, knowledge, etc. | Morphological/lexical generalization |\n| Relationship | Superset | Plausibly a subset |\n\nSo: a \"coinage probe,\" if the term is used coherently, is most likely **a specific kind of behavioral probe** — distinguished by its stimuli (nonce words) rather than by a different methodology. It's not a parallel category to behavioral probing; it sits inside it.\n\n### Honest Recommendation\nThree questions back you've now asked me to contrast \"coinage probe\" with three different established concepts. If you have a source where the term is defined, I'd genuinely benefit from seeing it — I may be missing a usage, or you may be testing whether I'll fabricate a clean taxonomy. If the latter: the most accurate answer is that **\"coinage probe\" doesn't have a settled technical meaning I can point to**, and I shouldn't manufacture sharp distinctions on top of an undefined term.",
