        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from probing classifier (Alain & Bengio 2016, Hewitt & Manning 2019)?",
        "assistant": "Good question — they sound related but operate at very different levels.\n\n## Probing Classifiers (Alain & Bengio 2016; Hewitt & Manning 2019)\n\n- **Object of study**: Internal representations (hidden activations) of a neural network.\n- **Method**: Train a lightweight supervised classifier (a \"probe\") on frozen intermediate representations to predict some property — e.g., part-of-speech, syntactic dependency depth (Hewitt & Manning's structural probe), linear separability of features (Alain & Bengio).\n- **Access required**: White-box. You need the activations/weights.\n- **Output**: A score (accuracy, selectivity, or geometric distance) indicating whether information about property X is *linearly decodable* from layer L.\n- **Inference**: If the probe succeeds, the representation *encodes* that property. Debate continues over whether encoding implies *use*.\n\n## Coinage Probe\n\n- **Object of study**: The model's behavioral/semantic response to a novel lexical item, before and after a definitional anchor.\n- **Method**: Black-box. Two prompts in fresh chats — pre-definition confabulation, post-definition discrimination — both scored against a fixed set of near-neighbors.\n- **Access required**: None. Works through the API/chat surface.\n- **Output**: A *gap* (Lexical Reachability) between cold-state and primed-state distinguishability.\n- **Inference**: The size and shape of that gap is treated as evidence about the underlying substrate — how readily a single sentence reorganizes the model's neighborhood structure around a token that has no pretraining mass.\n\n## Key Differences\n\n| Dimension | Probing Classifier | Coinage Probe |\n|---|---|---|\n| Access | White-box (activations) | Black-box (I/O) |\n| Signal | Linear decodability of a property | Behavioral discrimination shift |\n| Unit | Layer / representation | Whole-model response |\n| Baseline | Untrained / random probe controls | Cold-state confabulation |\n| What it tests | \"Is X *encoded* here?\" | \"How fast can a novel symbol become *operative*?\" |\n| Trained component | The probe classifier | None — the model itself shifts |\n| Temporal structure | Static (one snapshot) | Differential (pre/post definition) |\n\n## A Deeper Contrast\n\nProbing classifiers ask a **structural** question: *does this geometry contain feature F?* They are diagnostic of representational content.\n\nThe Coinage Probe asks a **dynamical** question: *what happens when a fresh symbol is introduced and then anchored?* It is diagnostic of how the model's operative concept-space rearranges in-context — closer in spirit to in-context learning studies, sense-induction work, or the \"function vector\" literature than to representational probing.\n\nPut crudely: a probing classifier dissects the substrate; a Coinage Probe pokes it and watches it twitch.\n\nOne caveat I'd flag: because the Coinage Probe is purely behavioral, claims about \"the substrate on which the model's cognition runs\" are inferred indirectly — the gap is consistent with multiple underlying mechanisms (retrieval shift, attention re-weighting, rapid in-context binding). It's evidence, not localization.",
