        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from behavioral probe / capability evaluation?",
        "assistant": "Good question — this is where the Coinage Probe is most likely to be mistaken for something more familiar, so the distinctions matter.\n\n## Behavioral Probes / Capability Evaluations\n\n- **Object of study**: Whether the model *can do X* — answer trivia, solve math, follow instructions, refuse harmful requests, etc.\n- **Method**: Construct a benchmark of inputs with known correct outputs (or rubrics); score the model's responses.\n- **Unit of analysis**: Task performance, aggregated across items.\n- **Baseline**: Human performance, prior models, chance, or a fixed threshold.\n- **What's varied**: The *input distribution* (different tasks, difficulties, domains).\n- **Inference**: \"The model has/lacks capability C at level L.\"\n\nExamples: MMLU, BIG-Bench, HELM, GSM8K, instruction-following evals, red-team probes, persona/jailbreak tests.\n\n## Coinage Probe\n\n- **Object of study**: How a *single novel symbol* is positioned in the model's operative concept-space, and how that positioning shifts under a minimal definitional intervention.\n- **Method**: Two matched measurements against a fixed neighbor set, separated by one sentence of definition.\n- **Unit of analysis**: A *gap* — Lexical Reachability — not a score.\n- **Baseline**: The model's own cold-state response (it is its own control).\n- **What's varied**: The *epistemic state of the model* with respect to one token, holding everything else fixed.\n- **Inference**: Something about how the substrate absorbs and operationalizes a fresh symbol.\n\n## Key Differences\n\n| Dimension | Behavioral Probe / Eval | Coinage Probe |\n|---|---|---|\n| Question form | \"Can it do X?\" | \"How does it move when nudged?\" |\n| Quantity measured | Accuracy / pass rate | Differential (pre vs. post) |\n| Control | External (humans, other models) | Internal (same model, cold-state) |\n| Stimulus | Many items, known answers | One coined term, no ground-truth answer |\n| Correctness | Defined by task | Not defined — distinguishability is the signal |\n| Scaling logic | Aggregate over a distribution | Resolution comes from a *single* well-chosen probe |\n| Novelty role | Often controlled away (contamination concern) | The point of the instrument |\n\n## A Deeper Contrast\n\nA capability eval treats the model as a **function under test**: fix the input distribution, measure output quality, compare. It is fundamentally a *performance* instrument.\n\nA Coinage Probe treats the model as a **system whose state can be perturbed**: introduce a symbol that *cannot* have been in pretraining, observe where it lands by default, then add one sentence and observe where it lands now. It is a *displacement* instrument.\n\nTwo consequences follow:\n\n1. **Contamination inverts**. For benchmarks, prior exposure to test items is a fatal confound. For a Coinage Probe, prior exposure is *impossible by construction* — the term is coined — which is why the cold-state measurement is meaningful at all.\n\n2. **No ceiling, no ground truth**. A capability eval needs a correct answer. A Coinage Probe doesn't; it only needs the neighbor set to be stable across the two measurements. The instrument reads a *change*, not a *correctness*.\n\n## Where They Could Be Confused\n\n- A \"novel-word understanding\" benchmark (give the model a made-up word + definition, test comprehension) *looks* like a Coinage Probe but is actually a capability eval — it scores post-definition performance against a ground truth, with no cold-state arm and no Reachability gap.\n- Red-team probes that test whether a model can be moved off a default also have a pre/post structure, but the quantity of interest is a *threshold crossing* (did it comply?), not a continuous gap measured against a fixed neighborhood.\n\nPut crudely: capability evals ask *what the model knows*; the Coinage Probe asks *how cheaply a new thing can become known-shaped to it*.\n\nThe same caveat from before applies: because the signal is behavioral, the gap is consistent with several underlying mechanisms (in-context binding, attention re-weighting toward the definition, retrieval of nearest analogues). The Coinage Probe localizes a phenomenon; it does not, on its own, identify its cause.",
