        "user": "How does \"coinage probe\" differ from lexical-acquisition test?",
        "assistant": "Good question — this is the closest neighbor yet, and the contrast is sharper than it first looks.\n\n## Lexical-Acquisition Tests\n\nA family of paradigms, from developmental psycholinguistics through NLP eval:\n\n- **Developmental origin**: \"Fast mapping\" studies (Carey & Bartlett 1978), wug tests (Berko 1958), novel-word learning under varying exposure conditions.\n- **NLP descendants**: Few-shot word-learning benchmarks, definition-modeling tasks, nonce-word evals (e.g., the \"wug\" test adapted for LMs), Chronicles-of-Narnia-style learning-from-context tasks.\n- **Object of study**: Whether and how an agent *acquires* a new lexical item — its meaning, syntactic class, morphological behavior, or extensional referents.\n- **Method**: Expose the learner to a novel word in some controlled context (ostensive definition, sentence frames, paired examples), then test downstream usage — production, comprehension, generalization, inflection.\n- **Quantity measured**: Acquisition success — did the learner end up with a usable representation of the word?\n- **Inference**: Claims about *learning mechanisms* — fast mapping, mutual exclusivity, syntactic bootstrapping, statistical learning.\n\n## Coinage Probe\n\n- **Object of study**: Not whether the word is acquired, but the *geometry of the gap* between cold-state and post-definition response, treated as a readout of the substrate.\n- **Method**: Two matched measurements against a fixed neighbor set; one sentence of definition between them.\n- **Quantity measured**: Lexical Reachability — a differential.\n- **Inference**: About the *substrate*, not the *learner-as-agent*.\n\n## Key Differences\n\n| Dimension | Lexical-Acquisition Test | Coinage Probe |\n|---|---|---|\n| Framing | Learner acquires meaning | System is displaced by a symbol |\n| Success criterion | Correct usage / extension | Distinguishability shift (no \"correct\") |\n| Cold-state arm | Usually absent or trivialized | Constitutive |\n| Neighbor set | Implicit (whatever the test items use) | Named, fixed, central to the measurement |\n| What \"definition\" is for | Teaching signal | Minimal perturbation |\n| Theoretical target | Acquisition mechanism | Substrate dynamics |\n| Output type | Score on post-exposure tasks | Pre/post gap against fixed neighbors |\n| Ground truth | Required (the word's intended meaning) | Not required |\n\n## The Decisive Contrast\n\nA lexical-acquisition test treats the novel word as a **target** — there is a meaning the learner is supposed to end up with, and the experiment measures convergence toward it. The definition (or context) is a *teaching input*; the test items afterward measure *uptake*.\n\nA Coinage Probe treats the novel word as an **instrument** — it has no intended meaning beyond what the single sentence stipulates, and even that sentence is not graded for \"uptake.\" The definition is a *perturbation*, not a lesson. What's measured is how the model's neighborhood structure rearranges, against a fixed reference frame the experimenter chose.\n\nTwo structural consequences:\n\n1. **The neighbor set is load-bearing in the Coinage Probe but incidental in acquisition tests.** A lexical-acquisition test could in principle ask any downstream question (Can you use it in a sentence? Pick the picture it refers to?). A Coinage Probe is *defined by* the named near-neighbors — they are the coordinate system in which Reachability is read.\n\n2. **A lexical-acquisition test can fail; a Coinage Probe cannot fail in the same sense.** If a learner doesn't acquire the word, the acquisition test returns a low score — failure of the learner. If a model shows no Reachability gap, the Coinage Probe returns a small number — that *is* the finding, not a failure. The instrument has no notion of \"the model got it wrong.\"\n\n## Where They'd Be Confused\n\n- A nonce-word definition-then-comprehension eval (give the model \"a *zib* is a small flightless bird,\" then ask \"is a zib a kind of mammal?\") looks superficially like a Coinage Probe. It isn't, because: (a) it grades against the stipulated meaning, (b) it has no cold-state arm, (c) the neighbors aren't a fixed reference set held constant across two measurements.\n- Conversely, a Coinage Probe could be *mistaken* for a degenerate acquisition test in which the experimenter forgot to specify ground truth. The point is that the absence of ground truth is the design, not an oversight.\n\nPut crudely: a lexical-acquisition test asks *did the word get learned?*; a Coinage Probe asks *what shape does the model take when a word is dropped into it and then lightly anchored?* The former is about the word arriving at a meaning; the latter is about the model revealing itself in how it receives the word.\n\nSame standing caveat: the gap is behavioral evidence about substrate dynamics, not a direct measurement of them. Multiple underlying mechanisms — in-context binding, attention to the defining sentence, retrieval of nearest analogues, prior over definitional form — can produce similar Reachability signatures and would need separate work to disentangle.",
